{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_jasper_ver01/data/sn84024271/00383344724/1930010201/0603.xml":{"full_text":"IFOR CHANCERY CLERK\nI hereby announce myself as a candidate for I\nChancery Clerk of Holmes County to fill the\nvacancy caused by the recent Lragedy.\nYour vote and influence will be greatly\nappreciated.\nRespectfully,\nGORDON ASHLEY\nLouisiana Oil Corp.\nI Ians Oil Well Test\nOn Acreage At West\nisual interest is attached to the\ng of a large block of acreage com\ng around 12,000 acres in the vicin\nWest and lying in Holmes and\ni counties, by the Louisiana Oil\nration, according to Allen G. Thur\nof Shreveport, La., who was in\ngton last week conferring with of\ni of the Holmes County Develop\nCo., at Lexington, also large hold\nacreage in the northeastern sec\nof this county.\nording to the visiting representa\n;he leases all stipulate that the be\nlg of a well will be undertaken on\nfore November 1, 1930 but that in\nents a test will be made as soon\nis possible to arrange all details\nlling in this newly acquired acre\nThe block under lease by the\niana company will measure about\n9s wide and 8 miles long.\n:h activity is ejected in the field\naccording to local followers of\nof this nature, and the territory\nconsideration offers many sur\nfbrmations that indicate flattering\nsets. Several outcroppings of shale\nrenounced faults and domes, have\nlargely responsible for several\ntions of foreign representatives\ngeologists who have inspected the\nory repeatedly during the last six\nis. Recordings and findings in\nhave been made by several geolo\nthat are recognized, and the area\nd to contain some of the best in\nons of oil bearing stratas in the\nHolmes County Development Co.,\n>sed of local business leaders in\nounty, have thousands of acres\nlease beginning north of Owens\njxtending north to the Carroll\ny line. It is planned to develop\njritory as soon as satisfactory ar\nments can be perfected for drill\nSeveral leading geologists and\nsentatives of drilling companies\nobtained details of the structure\na view of future activity in acre\nontrolled by the development com\nfind it in the Classified column.\nLexington Merchants\nSend New Year Greet\nings to All Patrons\nUshering in the New Year with an\noptimism prevailing among the best\nfriends of Lexington and surrounding\ntrade territory, the local merchants of\nthis city have arranged two full pages\nin this issue of The Advertiser to send\ngreetings to the public.\nThey have been encouraged during\n1929 by your patronage and cooperation\nand wish to assure you that 1930 is be\ning anticipated for even greater busi\nness than the past year. They shall\ncontinue to practice the ideals of busi\nness and maintain the high standards\nof service, quality, value and courtesy\nthat gains for them increasing patron\nagen so ably shown them by your trust\nand confidence.\nWith your aid they are looking for\nward to the New Year as one of great\nprogress and development for the com\nmunity and their sincere messages\nshould be read by every citizen of the\ncommunity, they have served so well,\nNow is- the time to start working\nharder 'than ever for the growth and\nprosperity, loyalty and continued ex\npansion of local trade and cooperation\nwith your local merchants who offer\nyou their service 365 days in the year.\nIt is a matter that should receive your\nconsideration at all times. Keeping a\ncommunity spirit alive is only a matter\nof giving the home merchants and busi\nness firm3 preference in your trade.\nEach accomplishment along this line\nrecords glowing reports at the year\u2019s\nend and is a valuable asset to any good\ntown. Lexington is your town\u2014the\nlocal merchants, your friends. Resolve\ntoday to work for your community and\nits trade, and you will enjoy a Happy\nNew Year from beginning to end.\nO. E. S. INSTALLATION JANUARY a\nFriday night, January 3 at 7:15 o\u2019clock\nthe Lexington chapter of the Eastern\nStar will hold a regular meeting, ac\ncording to announcement made by Mrs\nMary Stigler, secretary.\nThe newly elected officers will be in\nstalled at this time and a full attend\n1 ance is desired in every respect.\nHOLMES COUNTY CONTINUES\nPROGRESSIVE GROWTH AND\nPROSPERITY SURVEY SHOWS\nALL COMMUNITIES REFLECT INCREASED BUSINESS,\nBUILDING AND SOUND AGRICULTURAL PROGRAMS;\nLEADERS OPTIMISTIC FOR COMING YEAR\nA business and economic survey oi\nHolmes county shows a bright outlook\nfor the whole area, with bank deposits\naggregating $3,G55.000 and total re\nsources over $4,513,000, a slight increase\nover available figures of similar dates\nlast year. Every bank in the county re\nports fine collections and good condi,\ntions. Many of their customers have not\nsold all of their cotton which will ma\nterially increase deposits. However all\nare free in stating that agriculture is on\na better footing due to feed crops raised\nand debts at low levels where existing.\nIn road construction Beat 1 has com\npleted a 12 mile graveled road from Lex\nington south in new territory toward\nthe beat line of No. 2 at a cost of $60,\n000.00. Road District No. 4 in south\nwestern Holmes has also completed a\nroad serving that area embracing around\nj 14 miles at a similar cost. Durant,\ngrowing little city on the eastern wing\nof the county is planning an $85,000.00\npaving program to add to their $67,000\npaved streets.\nCrop yields have been the largest\never known all over the county, and\nfarmers have profited largely through\nearly sales and liquidation of debts.\nHolmes county boasts of seven large\ncommunities of the county, aside from\nthe interior towns and trading posts\nand are summarized as follows:\nj Lexington\u2014Unusually good business\n1 conditions and collections. A $25,000\ncounty record room has been built; and\nMerchants and Farmers Bank and Trust\no., declared a $50,000 cash diivdend\nDecember 24; the Lewis Grocer Co. has\nj increased its capital stock from $100,000\nto $200,000; bank deposits excellent and\nattaining new high levels; many new\nresidences completed as well as several\nbusiness houses added; business outlook\nfine for another year,\nj Durant\u2014An $85,000 paving program\nplanned; truck farming and dairying ad\nding to farm incomes, serving to pay\nas-go operations; much activity in home\nbuilding; completion of $5,000 post of\nfice; remodelling of several business\nI houses; a steady payroll from the Illi\n(nois Central shops, as well as planing\ni mill and other local industries; a new\nlaundry, hotel and other enterprises\nI added.\nHerbert Steele Breaks\nKnee In Auto Crash\nSaturday night between 7 and 8 o\u2019clock\nHerbert Steele, son of Mr. and Mrs. T.\nL. Steele, of this city, suffered a disas\ntrous car wreck and painful injury,\nwhen the car in which he was driving\ncrashed into a standing truck near H.\nB. McGee\u2019s farm on the Tchula-Lexing\nton highway, which resulted in the frac\nture of his right knee cap, cuts about\nthe leg, body and head and complete de\nmolition of the automobile.\nAccording to members of the family,\nMr. Steele met a car with bright lights\nthat blinded him. As he dimmed his\nlights to approach cautiously, he failed\nto see two tgucks that had stopped on\nthe road, before he had crashed into one\nof them loaded with household goods\nand in charge of a negro driver. The\nother truck was driven by a white man,\ni who also left the scene immediately af\nter young Steele suffered his accident,\ni He was later halted in Lexington but\nj told officers that he had not stopped\nto converse with the colored driver.\nMr. Steele managed to free himself\nfrom the car and flagged a couple from\nTchula who passed soon afterwards.\nThey brought him to Lexington and\nplaced him in the Community Hospital\nwhere he received medical aid.\nOn account of continued pain and\nfearing complications Mr. Steele was\ncarried to Memphis Tuesday night where\nhe will be placed in Dr. Campbell\u2019s\nclinic. He was accompanied by his\nfather, T. E. Steele and Rev. J. E.\nStephens. Complete examination will be\nmade immediately upon arrival and all\njoin in the hopes that he will soon be\nresored to his good health under the\nexpert tratment of this famed institu\ntion.\nJ. A. Stansbury was over from Cru\nger during the holidays.\n\u25a0BUM\nGoodman\u2014$125,000 additions to a\nfurther building program of Holmes\nJunior College; $35,000.00 water and\nsewerage installations completed; nat\nural gas connections now available;\nseveral planing and stave mills built re\ncently; improvements in business and\nresidential properties; an $8,000 Masonic\nhome to be constructed, several new\nmercantile firms entering business; pike\ncompleted east to connect with trade\nareas of Attala county; increased facili\nties in cotton ginnings.\nPickens Natural gas connections;\none-half million increase in yearly pay\nrolls by planing and stave mills enter\ning city; several residences and several\nbusiness houses built and improved;\nnew $5,000 home for motor agency; j\ngood business and no vacancies in busi-j\nness district, construction planned to\nhouse new' families moving to city ,-jind\ndemanding dwellings; hotel planned to\nserve the increased business growth and\ntransactions. Two new electric gins and\na bonded warehouse has increased Pick\nens cotton marketing facilities.\nWest\u2014Building of a $00,000 hardwood i\nand planing mill; increase in residences!\nand business properties; increase in\ndairying to patronize milk and cheese\nplants; plans under way for a 50 bale-a-\nday ginning capacity to be erected.!\nFarmers in fine shape from diversifica-\ntion programs, plenty of feedstuffs. In\ncreased logging activities to supply new\nmills.\nTchula\u2014Completion of installation\n$45,000 water and sewerage; new $20,\n000 motor agency headquarters, $10,000\nincrease in home building; good busi\nness conditions with many delta plant\ners with cotton yet to sell; collections j\ngood in business lines; large lumber\nmills utilizing raw products and good\nlumber shipments maintained.\nCruger\u2014Cotton crop biggest in years;\nno vacancies in home or business prop-\nerty. Several residences constructed,\nstead growth along conservation lines;\nincrease in business with reflected de-1\nposits in banking lines; collections good\nj and a good outlook for another season.\nM. F. Bank Holds\nElection of Officers;\nExcellent Statement\nAt a meeting held today by the board\nof directors of the Merchants and Farm\ners Bank and Trust Company, election\nof officers were held for the coming\nyear, according to Morris Lewis, presi\ndent of the institution; and one of the\nleading capitalists of this section.\nOfficers named were as follows: Mor\nris Lewis, president; W. If. Meek, N. B\nHooker, W. It. Ellis, H. H. Johnson,\nvice-presidents; J. W. Latham, cashier;\n\\V. D. Wilson, assistant cashier.\nThe board of directors chosen were\nas follows: Morris Lewis, W. M. Meek\nN. B. Hooker, W. K. Ellis, H. II. John\nson, S. J. Fisher and H. L. Nichols.\nThe Merchants and Farmers Bank and\nTrust Co., declared a 50 per cent divi\ndend on December 24, and $50,000.00 in\ncash was paid to stockholders as a\nChristmas gift. The institution is cap\nitalized at $100,000.00 and has a surplus\nof $100,000.00, with undivided profits\nnet of S26.C02.77. Cash and sight ex\n\"\"\u2018V over a million dol\nlars .vitn deposits over a million and a\nhalf dollars.\nOn February 3, 1930, the Merchants\nand Farmers Bank and Trust Co., will\ncelebrate their twenty-fith anniversary.\n1 his Silver Anniversary will be observed\niy the bank, its officers, directors and\nstockholders in a substantial manner,\nstated Morris Lewis, and the occasion\nis being planned with anticipation by all\nmembers of the financial organization.\n\"e call attention to a half-page ad\nvertisement appearing elsewhere in the\nthe Merchants and Farmers Bank\npaper showing a condensed statement\nind Trust Company at the close of busi\nness December 31, 1929.\nRoyal Arch Masons\nElect Year\u2019s Officials\nAt an election held for the coming\ni ear the Lexington Royal Arch Chapter\nNo. 9 selected the following officials:\nr. *T *!?imett\u00bb eminent high priest;\nOr. H. L Martin, king; R. E. Wilburn,\nDllkc> captain of host; R.\nbtigler, principal sojourner; W. B\nhenna, royal arch captain; E. Cohen\nrfTnJ J- E- McRae, master\nd Xe\u2018 L- McRae, master of 3rd\nI. L- Jordan, treasurer; C\nsentinel1\u2019 secretary= c- S. Bowman,\nllllliiiiiiiiiimiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiii\nt I\nBarr-Gwin Co. Give\nPublic First View\nOf New 1930 Ford\nBarr-Gwin Co., local Ford dealers,\nwere hosts Tuesday to hundreds of in\nterested visitors who visited their show\nrooms to inspect the new Ford that\nrepresented the new body types and\ncolors, introduced to the public for the\nfirst time and as a further introduction\nof the types that will follow.\nAccording to Mr. Barr numerous fea\ntures are included in \u2018he new model\nthat embraces the c.p' re line of cars\nmanufactured by thy well known motor\ncompany. New rustless steel, new\nstreamlines, roomier bodies, larger fen\nders, deeper and taller radiator, smaller\nwheels with larger cushioning tires, and\na variety of new color tones, with hun\ndreds of minor details included in a\npopular automobile, so favorable known\nby the motoring public, is presented- in\nthe new 1930 Ford.\nContinuing Mr. Barr stated that the\nnew Ford with its outstanding mechani\ncal performance, now adds new grace\nof line and cantou.'.. which has always\nreflected polic. \\t the Ford Motor\nCo., in constantly improving and givrtig\ngreater value far above the price aslled\nfor motor transportation.\nThe new model is of great beauty and\ncaused many visitations of owners and\nprospects alike, concluded Mr. Barr, who\nare always alert to the modern means\nof economical transportation.\nWill Hocut Expired\nSuddenly Last Week\nWill Hocut, farmer of near Lexington,\nwas found dead in the bed Saturday\nmorning, December 21 and at first Tt\nwas thought that he had committed\nsuicide. Sheriff Ellis and C. K. Reid,\njustice of the peace, were summoned\nand upon investigation, it was found\nthat he died from heart trouble. His\npistol was under his pillow and had not\nbeen fired.\nSeveral months ago, deceased\u2019s wife\nended her life early one morning which\nprompted many to believe that the\nhusband had committed a similar act.\nFuneral services were held at Har\nland\u2019s Creek cemetery, conducted by\nRev. A. E. Lucus.\nDeceased is survived by four children,\none girl and three boys, also three\nsisters, Mrs. Robert Ferrell. Mrs. Rafe\nFerrell and Miss Lena Hocut, also four\nbrothers, Frank, Gid, Rich and Howard\nlloi-ut, all of the same community.\nIIIIII11lllllllI III IIII III IIIIIII III III III III Mill Vf\nI New Year\nGreetings!\nMay 1930 be the happiest\nand most prosperous year\nof your experience is our\nwish for each of you.\nPEOPLES DRUG STORE\nWilliams Johnson, Propr\u2019s\nQuality First Service Always I\nLexington Mississippi j\nWALLS and ceilings\npainted with LOWE\n11ROTHERS MELLOTONE\nFlat Wall Paint will give\nyour rooms a restful atmos\nj phere.\nMellotone is an oil paint\nwithout lustre and is made\nin a wide range of attractive\nshades and tints which lend\nthemselves to an almost end\nless number of color combi\nnations in both plain and\nfancy effects.\nVery easy to clean.\nCome in and get a free\nbooklet on Home Decora\ntion.\nTHE FINCHER CO.\nHardware and Furniture\n^^^xington^^lississipp^^\n\n\nGREETINGS\na from a\nWHITE\u2019S CORNER GROCERY\np May Your New Year Be Like II\np Your Arithmetic: p\np \u2014Your Joys Added 1|\np \u2014Your Sorrows Subtracted p\np \u2014Your Worries Divided p\np \u2014Your Happiness Multiplied p\nWE WISH FOR ALL fj\nA VERY HAPPY NEW YEAR! p\nYes we have Cotton Seed Meal, Sacked H\nIh Hulls as well as a Complete Line of\np Other Feedstuffs. p\nlllllll!lllll!lll!llllllllllllll